<p><strong>Social Problems: A Down-to-Earth Approach, 11th Edition by James Henslin</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question 1: What is the main focus of the book "Social Problems" by James Henslin?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The book explores a range of social problems that affect individuals, communities, and societies. It examines the causes, consequences, and potential solutions to these problems from a sociological perspective.</p>
<p><strong>Question 2: How does Henslin define a social problem?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Henslin defines a social problem as a condition that threatens the well-being of a significant number of people in a society. It is a condition that is recognized as undesirable and for which there is a consensus that something should be done.</p>
<p><strong>Question 3: What are the different levels of social problems presented in the book?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Henslin identifies three levels of social problems:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Micro-level problems:</strong> Affect individuals or small groups within a society.</li>
<li><strong>Meso-level problems:</strong> Affect larger groups or organizations within a society.</li>
<li><strong>Macro-level problems:</strong> Affect society as a whole or a large portion of it.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Question 4: How does the book address the issue of global social problems?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The book recognizes that many social problems are not confined to specific countries or regions. It examines global issues such as poverty, inequality, environmental degradation, and terrorism.</p>
<p><strong>Question 5: What are some of the key sociological theories used to explain social problems?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The book introduces various sociological theories, including structural functionalism, conflict theory, and symbolic interactionism. These theories help explain the causes and consequences of social problems and guide potential solutions.</p>